label chapter17:

    # [Scene: The Glasshouse | Morning]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Drip of water, muffled gull calls, distant diesel hum of a delivery truck]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano—minor key, slow]
    "You are here because you chose to buy time. The paperwork is thick with promises and deadlines; the signatures are a temporary bridge. Rina stands near the doorway, sleeves rolled, talking with two people in clear-branded"
    "jackets—the NGO funders. Their voices are careful and certain, trained to make scarcity sound like opportunity."
    "Your fingers curl around the coral pendant at your throat without you thinking. It is small and warm; it keeps the rhythm of your pulse honest. Outside, the marsh breathes, unbothered by contracts. Inside, the air smells of wet soil, rust, and the faint antiseptic of printed packets."
    show rina_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rina_park "They can free up enough to hire forty locals—training, stipends, equipment. If we push the metrics, we can show quick wins within three months."

    "NGO Funder" "We need measurable outcomes. Survival of planted marsh grasses, volume of sediment retained, and a metrics report every six weeks. Payments are staged on benchmarks."
    "You fold the words inward, like a map being creased. The numbers promise relief—the kind that fits groceries and payroll—but the conditions clip their wings. Six-week benchmarks. Staged payments. A calendar that will outlive goodwill."
    "You clear your throat. Your voice is steadier than you feel."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "Maintenance is the spine of this work. If we plant and leave, the plants won't hold. The maintenance window needs to be guaranteed after the benchmarks."

    "NGO Funder" "We can extend advisory support for a year, but ongoing maintenance should be community-operated. Our grants are designed to catalyze, not to fund indefinitely."

    "You want to say" "Catalyze how? Catalyze into what?"

    mara_voss "We need a plan for when the grant ends. Training locals is good. But we have to lock in maintenance—either a local fund, municipal line item, or binding agreement with the developer."
    show mayor_rosa_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_rosa_alvarez "I'll push the council vote for a maintenance appropriation. I can't promise forever, but I can put it on the budget cycle."
    "The Mayor's face is a ledger of pressures—re-election, payroll, the hope she needs to sell to voters. Her assurance is real, but fragile."

    menu:
        "Insist on a written maintenance clause now":
            "You push the NGO rep with the firmness you save for data. He reaches for his tablet, eyes flicking briefly to Rina. The room tightens; he types and the draft clause appears—conditional, evasive, but present."
        "Accept the staged payments and move fast":
            "You nod for the cameras and the hopeful faces in the room. Rina exhales, visibly relieved. The funder smiles; momentum becomes a palpable thing, warm and immediate."

    # --- merge ---
    "You make a decision between the brittle security of a clause and the warmth of immediate work. Either way, the seed trays will be loaded onto the skiff by evening and the first crews will learn to plant the eelgrass by dawn."
    # [Scene: The Dock / Aster Skiff | Dawn — Montage over weeks]
    hide rina_park
    hide mara_voss
    hide mayor_rosa_alvarez

    scene bg ch15_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Hammering, low laughter, the slap of water against hulls, a radio murmuring weather updates]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low strings with a hesitant rhythm]
    "Work arrives like sunlight: blunt, demanding, necessary. You find yourself teaching more than modeling now—how to knot a planting line, how to read the soft give of silt, how to coax seedlings into place where the"
    "tide will accept them. Nia is there on the second week, boots caked to her knees, eyes endlessly curious. Tomas brings coffee and stories that smell of oil and old rope."
    "You catalog everything with the same rigor you used for grant proposals—before dawn, after lunch, while the crews eat soggy sandwiches on overturned crates. You record sedimentation rates, wave energy, survival percentages. Each number is a"
    "small victory: twenty percent survival at one site, fifty at another. The funders beam; the NGO donors circulate the images."
    "Developer reps visit the headland and watch the crews through binoculars. Their faces are unreadable—trained, like everyone else in negotiation, to present calm. You notice how they point to the planted sections in meetings: a photo,"
    "a proof, a shield. At town hall, one of them says, almost conversationally, 'You see? These mitigations prove the site's viability for broader development.' The line is a knife wrapped in paper."
    show elias_eli_calder at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_eli_calder "They're hiring my cousin for the crew, Mara. He's getting a week's pay he didn't have last month. That's real. I don't want to throw that away."
    "You study his face—warmth, worry, a practical calculus that measures mouths fed and bills paid. You want him to see the holes in the plan: dependence on temporary funds, the political ease of a good photo,"
    "the desertion of maintenance when the contracts dry up. But his perspective is immediate, and it hurts to ask him to prioritize future ghosts over present hunger."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "I know. That's why I pushed for more training days—not just planting. If people can be stewards, maybe they can keep it up after grants end."

    elias_eli_calder "And what if 'stewards' means unpaid labor later? What if the town becomes a maintenance contractor with no budget? I'm tired of promises that become my uncle's unpaid nights on his boat."
    "Your words tangle; you both talk faster, interrupting, because this is not just policy—it's the shape of the life you share with this place."

    elias_eli_calder "I don't distrust what you're doing. I just—I'm trying to imagine how we keep going when the money stops."

    mara_voss "We build local ownership. We find service contracts—"

    elias_eli_calder "Or we plan for the impossible—someone to come through with a long-term fund. Because 'build local ownership' is a feel-good sentence if the budget disappears."
    "There is a pause where neither of you wants to say the next thing: that jobs funded by grants are jobs that can evaporate. That people who work for hope can be left unpaid when the hope moves on."

    menu:
        "Allocate the last training funds to maintenance contracts":
            "You sketch a quick amendment in your notebook and take it to Rina. She studies it, brow furrowed, then nods—it's a slower metric but defensible. Elias \'Eli\' Calder squeezes your shoulder, not triumphant but relieved."
        "Push for more hires and optics to keep momentum":
            "You sign the hires sheet with a trembling hand. The crowd will cheer; the cameras will love it. Elias \'Eli\' Calder's face falls for a second, then he masks it with a frown that doesn't reach his eyes."

    # --- merge ---
    "You make a choice that will ripple. The crews applaud, the photos circulate, and the town tastes a small, clean victory."
    # [Scene: The Headland / Ribbon-Cutting | Bright Afternoon]
    hide elias_eli_calder
    hide mara_voss

    scene bg ch15_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A crowd claps; a microphone squeals; gulls wheel. A distant jackhammer starts up as if to puncture the applause.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Brass fanfare—bright, brittle]
    "Mayor Rosa: cuts the ribbon with practiced flourish. Cameras flash; the NGO posts the photos with captions about community resilience. Rina hugs you, exhausted and proud. The developer rep stands to the side and offers a smile that is both polished and strategic."

    "Developer Rep" "This is a promising start. As construction proceeds on the less-sensitive zones, we'll ensure there is minimal disruption to the restored areas. We appreciate the partnership."
    "You watch his mouth shape the words. In the crowd, a developer-engineer flips through plans; you notice the stamped approval lines. The mitigations have become proof that development can go forward."
    "Later, when the donors' funding schedule reaches its end, the payments taper. The promised municipal appropriation lands as a line item for one year, then contracts tighten. You watch the maintenance rosters shrink as grant workers"
    "take other jobs. The neatly planted grasses begin to fray in places where people can no longer tend them: crabgrass takes a foothold in one bed; a wave rips a section loose in another."
    show rina_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rina_park "They loved the numbers at first. Visibility moved donations. But the foundation's board wants shorter reporting cycles and 'evidence of independence.' They pulled matching funds. We can appeal, but—"
    "You want to be able to stitch a plan that keeps everything alive. Instead, you sift through a list of cancelled maintenance days and budget lines that are promising in a future you can no longer guarantee."
    "You walk the marsh at low tide and find a row of planted eelgrass wrinkled and thin. Nearby, a developer's temporary grading fence squeezes the channel a few meters inland—an engineering justification filed by someone who will point to this very photo and say, 'Look, mitigation has happened.'"
    show old_tomas_calder at right:
        zoom 0.7

    old_tomas_calder "You did what you could, Mara. Made it better than nothing. But better isn't forever."
    "You sit beside him, the wood cold through your jeans. The marsh smells like old rain and the honest rot of organic things. You feel hollow and full at once: proud of the hands you put to work, sickened by the precarity you've invited."
    "Elias 'Eli' Calder finds you again, later that week, leaning against the Glasshouse glass. He holds a canvas bag, an airline patch peeking from inside. His shoulders are set in a way that says he has"
    "made a decision that isn't about you, and that it will still alter your world."
    show elias_eli_calder at center:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_eli_calder "There's a seasonal crew upstate that needs someone experienced. It's steady. I can send money home, Mara. I can keep my uncle afloat from there."
    "You feel the room tilt. For a moment every fear and sacrifice you've measured becomes a single point of weight in your chest."
    hide rina_park
    show mara_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "Are you leaving?"

    elias_eli_calder "Not because I don't believe in this. Because I do. But I can't watch my family get squeezed out waiting for someone else's calendar. I need stability now."
    "You search his face for the thing that would make him stay: an absolute promise, an answer that rearranges budgets and timelines. There isn't one."

    elias_eli_calder "I didn't choose these grants. I didn't choose their clocks. But I choose food on my table. I'm sorry."
    "You have no rejoinder that will change the trade-off, because the trade-off isn't yours alone to cancel. It is a ledger written in other people's needs, in tides and job postings and the slow mercy of budgets."
    "You clasp your coral pendant until it hurts. The metal is warm from your palm. You think of the seedlings that lived and the ones that didn't, of the faces that smiled into the cameras and the faces that disappeared when the checks stopped."
    # [Scene: Marsh Fringe | Grey Twilight — Months Later]
    hide old_tomas_calder
    hide elias_eli_calder
    hide mara_voss

    scene bg ch15_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind hissing through reeds, a faint thrumming of distant machinery, the soft creak of a buoy line]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low cello—resolute, grieving]
    "You stand at the edge where water meets mud and imagine an alphabet of obligations: to seedlings, to neighbors, to the town you love, to the person you shared evenings and frustrations with. The grant bought"
    "jobs—real, human jobs that paid rent for months. But the funding framed the work in a cadence foreign to the tides. It left you with a visible scaffold and an invisible debt."
    "Nia appears beside you, boots silent in the wet. She looks smaller now, older in a way that has nothing to do with years. Her eyes scan the marsh, landing on a tuft of slim green that remains stubbornly upright."
    show nia_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    nia_voss "Does this mean we'll still have fish for summer next year?"
    "You want to answer with certainty, to hand her the kind of truth that can sit in a child's chest and become the axis of hope."
    show mara_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_voss "It means we have a chance. A better chance than before. But chances need people to keep them."
    "She nods slowly, the mechanics of adulthood already at work in the angle of her jaw. Her faith is practical; she wants instructions, not platitudes."
    "You turn your face to the headland where the developer's floodlights blink like a city that does not sleep. In the slick, bright images the town put on its social feeds, everything looks resolved. The reality"
    "is partial: patches of marsh hold, others don't; families found work for a season, then looked again for the next paycheck; the developer proceeds with eyes that catalog visual mitigation as permission."
    "You could rage at the foundations, at the boards that cut checks and then demanded the stories be clean. You could rail at the Mayor, at Rina, at yourself. Rage would be honest, but it would not plow the fields."

    "Instead, you go back to your notebook. You mark the coordinates of the strongest surviving beds. You circle them and write, in neat, stubborn script" "Priority—Maintain. Local stewardship trial."
    "You do not have a guarantee that the town will fund it. You do not have the power to make foundations care beyond their reporting cycles. But you have a map, and you have people who still show up when the sky threatens."
    "At twilight, when the marsh is mostly quiet, you walk the margins where water laps at your boots. The pendant bobs against your collarbone like a small bell. The tide leaves a bright line on the"
    "reed stems—a scar and a promise. You listen to the marsh breathe and know what you must do: keep tending, keep teaching, keep bargaining for the small continuities that matter."
    "You are tired. You are bruised. You are still here."
    hide nia_voss
    hide mara_voss

    scene bg ch15_3be532_5 at full_bg
